>>40627407
Ok, this is going to be harsh on a few points.

Thoughts need to be done consistently. In one place you have them as italicized dialogue (fine), but in another place it's non-italic.
There's a few missing commas, and in general this isn't a mortal sin. The problem is when a longer sentence isn't as clear without them. My preference is to use shorter sentences wherever possible. Running your text through Hemingway highlights longer sentences, but remember that only you can determine the pacing of your writing. If you need longer sentences, use them but write them well.
Pacing felt a little slow, and the sight/smell of the sensory could be punched up. After all, we are talking about motorcycles. And since I'm tweaking this point as well on a draft, feel the musculature! Ruby's big. How you write her cuffing a youngun should read differently than the cycle toss.

And last, that cantaloupe reference was jarring.

Anonymous Mon 02 Aug 2021 16:16:53 No.40627891 Report
Quoted By:
>>40627239
It is. The prompts (used to be) a good source for short flash-greentext ideas. A good number of the more popular stories presented in this here itt thread were coalesced in-part by ideas crowdsourced from simple questions about species, exoticism (with respect to tropes/species untrod here), setting, etc.
We've had sequences of threads dedicated to cape villains & heroes, superpowered waifur ensembles, post-apocalyptic settings that usually went into diesel punk/Mad Max territory, space opera and other sci-fi subgenres – you name it. If you're interested in discussing a genre from literary perspectives, it helps to be read on them somewhat. If you're looking for inspiration for your own ideas, I strongly recommend short story anthologies, which are cheap on Amazon. Reference materials for new writers are a mixed bag, but start with what's in the sticky and ask around.
One of the best ways to kick off a coherent dialogue on genre in the itt is to ask around for more stories that are similar to your favorites. Flesh out what it is that intrigues you most in your query – suburban romance is a broad and common genre here, so you'll really want to clarify the elements that draw you most, down to species and definable character archetype/personality.
